                    <a href="/ContactUs"><li>Contact Us</li></a>
                </ul>
                    <div class="container-Style">
                    <form>
                        <fieldset class="form-container">
                            <legend class="Contact-And-Help">
                                <a href="/CatCare">Cat Care</a>
                            </legend>

                            <ol type="1">
                                <li><h3>Feeding</h3>
                                    <ul id="ulColor" style="list-style-type: disc;">
                                        <li>Diet: Feed your cat a balanced diet with high-quality commercial cat food or a vet-approved homemade diet.</li>
                                        <li>Schedule: Provide meals at regular times each day. Kittens usually need to eat more frequently than adult cats.</li>
                                        <li>Portion Control: Follow the feeding guidelines on the food packaging or consult your vet to determine the correct portion size.</li>
                                    </ul>
                                </li>
                            
                                <li><h3>Exercise</h3>
                                    <ul id="ulColor" style="list-style-type: disc;">
                                        <li>Playtime: Cats need regular play sessions to stay active and mentally stimulated. Use toys like feathers, laser pointers, or interactive toys.</li>
                                        <li>Physical Activity: Provide opportunities for your cat to climb, scratch, and explore their environment.</li>
                                    </ul>
                                </li>
                            
                                <li><h3>Grooming</h3>
                                    <ul id="ulColor" style="list-style-type: disc;">
                                        <li>Brushing: Regularly brush your cat's coat to prevent matting and reduce shedding. Long-haired cats may need more frequent brushing.</li>
                                        <li>Nail Trimming: Trim your cat's nails regularly to prevent overgrowth and to protect furniture and skin.</li>
                                        <li>Ear Cleaning: Check and clean your cat's ears as needed to prevent wax buildup or infections.</li>
                                        <li>Dental Care: Brush your cat's teeth regularly and provide dental treats or toys to promote oral health.</li>
                                    </ul>
                                </li>
                            
                                <li><h3>Health Care</h3>
                                    <ul id="ulColor" style="list-style-type: disc;">
                                        <li>Vet Visits: Schedule regular vet check-ups for vaccinations, parasite control, and overall health assessments.</li>
                                        <li>Parasite Prevention: Use flea, tick, and worm prevention treatments as recommended by your vet.</li>
                                        <li>Spaying/Neutering: Consider spaying or neutering your cat to prevent unwanted litters and reduce certain health risks.</li>
                                    </ul>
                                </li>
                            
                                <li><h3>Training and Socialization</h3>
                                    <ul id="ulColor" style="list-style-type: disc;">
                                        <li>Litter Box Training: Introduce your cat to the litter box early and keep it clean. Place the box in a quiet, accessible location.</li>
                                        <li>Behavioral Training: Use positive reinforcement techniques to train your cat for behaviors like using scratching posts and coming when called.</li>
                                        <li>Socialization: Expose your cat to different people, environments, and handling to promote confidence and reduce stress.</li>
                                    </ul>
                                </li>
                            
                                <li><h3>Safety</h3>
                                    <ul id="ulColor" style="list-style-type: disc;">
                                        <li>Indoor Safety: Ensure your home is cat-proofed by securing toxic plants, chemicals, and small objects that could be swallowed.</li>
                                        <li>Collar and ID: Consider a breakaway collar with an ID tag that includes your contact information, even for indoor cats.</li>
                                        <li>Microchipping: For added security, consider microchipping your cat to increase the chances of being reunited if they get lost.</li>
                                    </ul>
                                </li>
                            
                                <li><h3>Mental Stimulation</h3>
                                    <ul id="ulColor" style="list-style-type: disc;">
                                        <li>Enrichment Activities: Provide puzzle feeders, catnip toys, and vertical spaces for climbing to keep your cat mentally stimulated.</li>
                                        <li>Interactive Play: Engage your cat in interactive play sessions using toys that mimic prey behavior.</li>
                                        <li>Rotation of Toys: Rotate toys regularly to keep your cat interested and prevent boredom.</li>
                                    </ul>
                                </li>
                            
                                <li><h3>Love and Attention</h3>
                                    <ul id="ulColor" style="list-style-type: disc;">
                                        <li>Affection: Show your cat love and affection through petting, grooming, and cuddling sessions.</li>
                                        <li>Quality Time: Spend quality time with your cat daily to strengthen your bond and understand their unique behaviors.</li>
                                        <li>Respect Boundaries: Respect your cat's need for personal space and quiet time.</li>
                                    </ul>
                                </li>
                            </ol>
                            

                        </fieldset>



                    </form>

                </div>
            </div>





        </main>

